Unchanged Impact to our thesis
Modest upside Financial results versus consensus
Modest revision higher Direction of next 12-month consensus EPS
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research

Shares are lower post- market as AI server strength was partially offset by mixed execution, driving a lower than expected July Q beat/full year guide. However, rev growth just hit a 3+ year high, EPS growth is sustaining at high teens Y/Y, and we still see path to positive est revisions. Remain OW.

AI server revs of \(\) 8.2\(B and full year guidance of\) \ \(20B\) was the standout of the quarter, and our checks point to likely upside vs. this target. Storage and PC execution was mixed in the quarter, though should improve in 2H. This negative mix led to an expectations miss with full year EPS guidance of \(\) 9.55\(below buy side bogeys. That said, stock is trading at\) 12x P/E for high - teens EPS growth and we see a path to positive est revisions in 2H. Ests are largely unchanged, with\) \ \(144\) PT implying 12.75x our \(\) 11.30\$ of FY27 EPS.

An expectations miss as strength in AI servers and uneven storage/PC execution brings the margin debate back into the forefront; Remain OW. Performance in the quarter was mixed, with strength in AI and traditional servers partially offset by uneven execution in Storage and PCs. The result was a modestly better July quarter and October quarter guide that straddled Consensus, with the revenue guidance midpoint \(2\%\) above but EPS midpoint \(4\%\) below Street. We're not surprised by this - DELL historically guides next quarter EPS conservatively - and with almost perfect regularity, beats the original Consensus expectation. However, when we step back and digest tonight's results, we'd still characterize the quarter as illustrating progress, with AI servers the clear standout, and DELL highlighting emerging strength in enterprise AI demand, double digit growth in traditional servers (in F2Q and FY26), and double digit growth in their midrange storage product and entire all- flash portfolio. Yes, margins face pressure from increasing AI server mix - this should not come as a surprise (and yet the stock is down \(5\%\) as a result) - but that is set to reverse in 2H, and if DELL can improve execution in US large enterprise and the overall PC business, then the story should get cleaner from here. Post- earnings our estimates don't change materially - we're at \(\) 9.60\(of EPS for the year and\) \ \(11.30\) in FY27, \(2\%\) and \(3\%\) above Street - and our PT remains \(\) 144\(, implying low - to - mid teens

% upside to our price target, with a path to \(\) 11.50- 12\(of earnings power in FY27 (and\) 20\% + \(upside) if execution can improve and mgmt can maintain cost discipline.

What we learned from DELL's F3Q26 earnings report: July Q revenue of \(\) 29.8B\(came in\) 1\% \(above MSE and\) 3\% \(above Street expectations. By segment, ISG landed\) 4\% \(ahead of MSE (7\% above Consensus), driven entirely by Al server upside (DELL recognized\) \ \(8.2B\) of Al server revenue in the quarter, above mgmt's prior \(\) 7B\(guidance), while Storage underperformed (missing MSE by\) 6\% \(. F2Q CSG revenue came in\) 2\% \(below MSE (\) \ \(12.5B\) vs. \(\) 12.7B\(MSE) and\) 3\% \(below Consensus expectations, driven by a\) 5\% \(miss in Consumer PC revenue and\) 1\% \(miss in Commercial PC revenue. F2Q non - GAAP gross margins of\) 18.7\% \((- 330bps Y/Y, - 290bps Q / Q)\) missed MSE and Consensus by 60 - 90bps, primarily a function of Al server revenue upside and storage underperformance. Despite the weaker than expected gross margins, the stronger revenue base and slightly lower opex (\) 3.3B vs. \(\) 3.7B\(MSE), resulted in non - GAAP EPS in - line with MSE (\) 2.32, 3c above Consensus). DELL guided F3Q26 revenue and EPS to\) 26.5 - 27.5B and \(\) 2.45+/- 10c, respectively, and FY26 revenue and EPS to\) 105 - 109B inclusive of \(\) 20B\(of Al server revenue (up from\) \ \(101 - 105B\) and \(\) 15B+\(of Al server revenue prior) and\) \ \(9.55+/- 25c\) (up from \(\) 9.40+/- 24c prior).

(+) Al server commentary strong across the board. Dell guided to full year Al server revenue ( \(20B\) above our \(18B\) expectations (though this aligns with our supply chain checks), spoke to an enterprise and sovereign pipeline growing double digits Q/Q (we know CSP demand is strong) with over 6700 unique customers in the pipeline (mostly on Blackwell), and highlighted that demand for enterprise Al is "immeasurable" with the most customers and most enterprise Al revenue recognized in a quarter (50% new customers, 50% returning) in F2Q. Additionally, DELL noted that Al server mix will improve in 2H, helping to drive Al server margins higher. Stepping back, we don't believe there is much debate on the strength of DELL's Al server business (outside of quarterly lumpiness) - it has significant momentum, will almost certainly outperform their \(20B\) target for the year (bull case is \(\) 25B+\(), and should continue to grow at a very healthy clip into 2026+.\)

(- ) More favorable mix in 2H driving improved margins, but cognizant of Al server upside potential. While CSG operating margins surprised to the upside in F2Q, ISG operating margins surprised negatively, with 8.8% the weakest ISG OPM in 5 quarters. Three key factors drove the weaker than expected quarterly margin - (1) Al server revenues upside vs. expectations, (2) storage underperformance, and (3) a material one-time cost associated with accelerating materials and reconfiguring their Al supply chain (Wistron moving GB rack production to Mexico). Looking to 2H, ISG operating margins should improve Q/Q from 2Q to 3Q and 3Q to 4Q as Al server margins modestly improve (mix, scale, no 1-timer), Storage grows 10% H/H and the relative mix of Al revenue within ISG decreases H/H. That said, we expect upside to mgmt's \(20B\) Al server guidance this year - mostly from returning CSP customers - and therefore would caution we're towards the lower end of management's 11- 14% ISG operating margin guidance for FY26.

(- ) HCI headwind masking solid DELL storage performance in the quarter. We were surprised to see DELL Storage down 3% Y/Y this quarter, as DELL was the second best performing Storage vendor in our July checks and both storage peers

that reported last night posted Y/Y revenue growth. Some of the Y/Y decline can be attributed to weaker than expected large enterprise demand in North America (which DELL needs to address), but the intentional shift from selling Dell HCI products to DELL IP is another factor. Under the good, SMB and International storage demand was strong, PowerStore and AT&T grew double digits Y/Y, and DELL expects DELL IP storage to outgrow the market in 2H (with expanding margins). Yes, guidance still implies Storage declines \(1 - 2\%\) Y/Y in 2H, but again, we attribute that primarily to the HCI shift, with \(10\%\) H/H Storage revenue growth \(\sim 2\) points above trailing 5 year seasonality.

\((\equiv)\) PC outlook a tad better than we expected. CSG missed our forecast in F2Q (1% Commercial miss, 5% Consumer miss) and mgmt acknowledged the need to improve execution, but F3Q guidance for MSD% Y/Y CSG revenue growth and a reiteration of LSD to MSD% Y/Y CSG revenue growth in FY26 is better than we expected and aligns with peers' more bullish PC commentary last night. That said, DELL has to execute to hit this target, though with COO Jeff Clarke now overseeing CSG, we feel very comfortable underwriting improved execution and a likely path to regaining market share, as we view Mr. Clarke as one of the best operators/executors we have encountered in the industry (as Michael Dell once said, Mr. Clarke possesses "tactical brilliance").

Dell Technologies Earnings Analysis
Core Ow As Gen Al Momentum + Capital Returns Accelerates
Key: - Historical Stock Performance Current Stock Price Price Target

DELL is a full stack technology provider managing more data than any other IT provider, which positions the company well to capitalize on the 'Data Era'. Despite the challenging Hardware spending environment, we see several factors that can drive upside to valuation and earnings, including, accelerating capital returns, best- in- class cost management, and perhaps most importantly, a ramping Gen Al story, as DELL capitalizes on rapidly accelerating Al Server demand, with a long runway for growth ahead.

Demand exceeds expectations in FY26. PC and enterprise infrastructure demand rebounds quicker than expected, driven by a better macro & Win 11 refresh activity. DELL gains share across PCs, servers, & storage. CSG grows HSD Y/Y in FY26 as Win 10 EOL approaches in Oct '25 and ISG grows double digits Y/Y in FY26 driven by demand for Al servers, greater compute needs & software defined storage, with revenue exceeding the COVID period. Cap returns accelerate.

Strong demand for Al Servers, PC market refresh, and accelerating shareholder returns unlocks value. Traditional infrastructure and CSG revenue grows LSD Y/Y in FY26. On the other hand, Al server demand continues to accelerate, growing \(100\% +\) Y/Y in FY26. Revenue grows \(13\%\) Y/Y in FY26 and \(6\%\) Y/Y in FY27. DELL accelerates buybacks & grows its dividend while investing in growth opportunities, and leverages Al internally to drive opex efficiency.

Demand deteriorates meaningfully and share gains prove short lived. A recession in CY25 causes a double dip in enterprise budget cuts, pressuring ISG & commercial PC results further, and consumer weakness drives a pushout of any PC recovery. DELL raises prices across the board to offset higher tariffs, cannibalizing demand while tariffs + macro uncertainty drives a slowdown in Al capex spend. Revenue declines LSD Y/Y and EPS declines MSD Y/Y in FY26. Stock trades to 9x P/E.
